prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
The essential requirements to achieve our goals can be summarized as follows. 1. Availability of 300-400 GHz band receivers to observe the strongest HCN line (J = 4-3) at 354.506 GHz. 2. High spatial resolution capable of observing Enceladus' plumes, not including its torus or Saturn's atmosphere, to identify the gas composition of the plumes. 3. High sensitivity to perform observations at low gas densities in the plumes of a small observing target, i.e., of ~1000 km-sized plumes. ALMA, based on its Cycle 2 specifications, is the only facility available that satisfies all of these requirements.
Observational configuration 4. This proposal is time critical. Enceladus can be observed from June to August from Chile. During this period, the distance on the celestial sphere between Enceladus and Saturn is greater than 1.4 × Saturn's radius. Thus, Enceladus will not be projected onto Saturn during the proposed observational time period. Because the distance from Earth to Enceladus will be closer (~9 AU) in June than in August (~10 AU) both in 2014 and 2015, the observations in June are preferable. The final Enceladus flyby of Cassini is planned for October 2015. To determine the INMS measurement configuration before the flyby, earlier observations in 2014 are preferable. 5. We propose to point the center of 12 m antenna FOV at 400 km below the surface of the south pole of Enceladus (0.1 arcsec-distance from its ephemeris) to maximize the sensitivity to the plumes. In the image synthesis, the continuum emission from Enceladus (a priori brightness model is available) will be subtracted from the measured visibilities to enable an improved image synthesis of the plume signal. Furthermore, in about 2/3 nights during the proposed time period, the distance between Saturn and Enceladus will be greater than 20 arcsec, which is the FOV size of the 12 m antenna. Thus, we prefer to observe Enceladus in these days. We will provide more detailed location information of the beam target and the preferable days for the observations if this proposal is approved. 6. To observe Enceladus' plumes, the synthesized beam size should be ~0.12 arcsec. Otherwise, the plume signal will be diluted by emission from Enceladus and the cold and empty sky. 7. The target gas is HCN emission at 354.506 GHz. To identify emission with an expected linewidth of 1 km s-1, we have select the 488 kHz spacing correlator configuration. 8. To detect the HCN line at 354.506 GHz with a 0.12 arcsec synthesized beam, the required sensitivities are 14.17, 7.09, and 4.72 mJy per pointing, respectively. The total required times for 1, 2, and 3σ observations, including for calibration-data acquisition, are estimated at 44 min, 1.4 hr, and 2.8 hr, respectively. Despite the uncertainty in the plumes' gas density, we will be able to determine whether or not HCN is present within a very reasonable observation time. 9. If no HCN were to be detected, we would be able to provide an upper limit of the HCN concentration in the plumes. The upper limits would be 0.3% and 0.2% relative to H2O for the observational times of 2.8 hr and 5.7 hr, respectively. Note that, as described in the Science Justification, the negative detection of HCN will also bring significant advances in the planetary formation theory (see Table 1). 10. We also propose to observe o-H2CO at 351.769 GHz, p-H2CO at 363.946 GHz, and p-H2CO at 365.363 GHz. Assuming that ~1% of H2CO is contained in the plume, the required observation times for a 1σ detection of these o- and p-H2CO lines become between 7 and 21 hr. However, the estimated observation times are sensitive to the amount of H2CO, which is highly uncertain. Thus, we include these lines in the list of the observations as an additional goal.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: Water-rich plumes erupting from Enceladus suggest the presence of an interior liquid ocean in the moon. Is Enceladus habitable? Are there any hydrothermal systems similar to those on Earth? In-deep investigations of its plumes could provide answers to these questions. However, Cassini is not able to identify a key molecule, HCN, which can probe the physical and chemical conditions of the ocean. We propose to determine whether HCN is present in Enceladus' plumes using the ALMA Band 7 receiver. Because HCN readily hydrolyzes in warm water (>50°C), a lack of HCN suggests that Enceladus would have possessed hydrothermal activity. A lack of HCN also requires the formation of organic materials in the interior. On the other hand, if HCN were to be detected, Enceladus would have been cold throughout its history. This suggests late formation of the Saturnian system (>5 Myr) after the genesis of the solar system under cold nebular conditions. This is the first proposal to assess habitability of icy satellites with a telescope. In either case whether or not HCN were to be detected, our observations would provide new views on habitability of Enceladus and the formation of Saturn.
